---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "PC Hardware Terms",
    "description": "PC hardware terms: GPU, CPU, RAM, SSD, bottleneck, thermal throttle."
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is GPU (Graphics Processing Unit)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The graphics card. It is the most critical component for gaming performance, entirely responsible for rendering the high-resolution images, complex textures, lighting, and 3D graphics you see on your monitor."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is CPU (Central Processing Unit)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The processor acts as the brain of the computer. In gaming, it handles all the underlying game logic, artificial intelligence, physics calculations, and tells the GPU what to render."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is RAM (Random Access Memory)?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Extremely fast, volatile short-term memory that the CPU uses to temporarily store the data it is actively working on. Having enough RAM ensures games run smoothly without stuttering as new assets are loaded."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="leeroyjenkins"
  title="PC Hardware Terms"
  description="PC hardware terms: GPU, CPU, RAM, SSD, bottleneck, thermal throttle."
  canonical="https://leeroyjenkins.quest/pc-hardware-terms"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>PC Hardware Terms</h1>
      <p>PC hardware terms: GPU, CPU, RAM, SSD, bottleneck, thermal throttle.</p>
    </div>


    <div class="card">
        <h3>GPU (Graphics Processing Unit)</h3>
        <p>The graphics card. It is the most critical component for gaming performance, entirely responsible for rendering the high-resolution images, complex textures, lighting, and 3D graphics you see on your monitor.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>CPU (Central Processing Unit)</h3>
        <p>The processor acts as the brain of the computer. In gaming, it handles all the underlying game logic, artificial intelligence, physics calculations, and tells the GPU what to render.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>RAM (Random Access Memory)</h3>
        <p>Extremely fast, volatile short-term memory that the CPU uses to temporarily store the data it is actively working on. Having enough RAM ensures games run smoothly without stuttering as new assets are loaded.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>SSD (Solid State Drive)</h3>
        <p>A storage device that uses flash memory, offering exponentially faster read and write speeds than traditional mechanical hard drives (HDDs). An SSD drastically reduces game load times and eliminates texture pop-in.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Bottleneck</h3>
        <p>A severe performance limitation that occurs when one critical component (e.g., an outdated CPU) is significantly slower than the rest of the system (e.g., a brand new, high-end GPU), preventing the faster components from operating at their full potential.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Thermal throttle</h3>
        <p>A built-in safety mechanism where a CPU or GPU automatically and drastically lowers its clock speed and performance to reduce heat output and prevent catastrophic physical damage when operating temperatures get dangerously high.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Overclocking</h3>
        <p>The advanced process of manually forcing a CPU, GPU, or RAM to run at a higher clock speed than the manufacturer's official specifications, increasing performance but also significantly increasing heat generation and power consumption.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Frame rate (FPS)</h3>
        <p>Frames Per Second. The frequency at which consecutive images (frames) are rendered by the GPU and displayed on the monitor. Higher frame rates result in noticeably smoother and far more responsive gameplay.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Vsync (Vertical Sync)</h3>
        <p>A display technology that artificially limits the game's frame rate to exactly match the monitor's refresh rate. While it eliminates screen tearing, it often introduces noticeable input lag, making it unfavorable for competitive gaming.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Refresh rate</h3>
        <p>Measured in Hertz (Hz), it is the maximum number of times per second a monitor can draw a new image. A 144Hz monitor can display up to 144 frames per second, providing a massive advantage in fast-paced games over standard 60Hz displays.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Resolution</h3>
        <p>The total number of pixels displayed on a screen, dictating image sharpness. Common resolutions include 1080p (Full HD), 1440p (QHD), and 2160p (4K). Higher resolutions require significantly more GPU power to run smoothly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Motherboard</h3>
        <p>The main printed circuit board of the computer. It connects all the critical hardware components together—the CPU, GPU, RAM, and storage—allowing them to communicate and receive power from the power supply.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>PSU (Power Supply Unit)</h3>
        <p>The component that converts power from the wall outlet into usable power for the internal PC parts. A high-quality PSU with enough wattage is essential for system stability and preventing sudden shutdowns during intense gaming.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>AIO (All-In-One Cooler)</h3>
        <p>A closed-loop liquid cooling system used primarily to cool the CPU. It consists of a pump block attached to the processor, connected via tubes to a radiator equipped with fans, offering excellent thermal performance and aesthetics.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Form factor</h3>
        <p>The physical size and standard layout of a motherboard and PC case. The most common sizes, from largest to smallest, are ATX, Micro-ATX (mATX), and Mini-ITX. The form factor dictates how many expansion slots and features are available.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>NVMe</h3>
        <p>Non-Volatile Memory Express. An interface protocol specifically built for incredibly fast solid-state drives that connect directly to the motherboard via PCIe slots, offering speeds vastly superior to older SATA SSDs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>PCIe (Peripheral Component Interconnect Express)</h3>
        <p>The high-speed interface standard used for connecting the graphics card, NVMe SSDs, and other expansion cards directly to the motherboard.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Airflow</h3>
        <p>The critical movement of cool air into the PC case and hot air out, managed by case fans. Proper airflow is absolutely essential to maintain low temperatures and prevent thermal throttling of the CPU and GPU.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Screen tearing</h3>
        <p>A distracting visual artifact that occurs when the GPU pushes out frames significantly faster or slower than the monitor's refresh rate, resulting in multiple frames being displayed on screen simultaneously, creating horizontal 'tears' in the image.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>G-Sync / FreeSync</h3>
        <p>Adaptive sync technologies developed by NVIDIA and AMD, respectively. They synchronize the monitor's refresh rate dynamically with the GPU's fluctuating frame rate output, eliminating screen tearing entirely without introducing the heavy input lag associated with Vsync.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>VRM (Voltage Regulator Module)</h3>
        <p>Crucial components on the motherboard and graphics card that ensure the CPU and GPU receive a steady, clean, and exact amount of voltage. High-quality VRMs are essential for stable overclocking.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>I/O Shield</h3>
        <p>The small, often frustrating metal plate installed in the back of the PC case that covers the gaps around the motherboard's external ports (USB, audio, ethernet) to protect against dust and electromagnetic interference.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>XMP / DOCP</h3>
        <p>Extreme Memory Profile. A setting in the motherboard's BIOS that allows RAM to run at its advertised high speeds rather than the slower default base speed. Failing to enable XMP leaves significant performance on the table.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Ray tracing</h3>
        <p>An extremely demanding advanced rendering technique that physically simulates the realistic behavior of light, creating incredibly lifelike reflections, shadows, and global illumination, requiring specialized hardware found in modern high-end GPUs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>DLSS / FSR</h3>
        <p>Deep Learning Super Sampling (NVIDIA) and FidelityFX Super Resolution (AMD). Advanced AI and spatial upscaling technologies that render the game at a lower resolution to massively boost frame rates, then intelligently upscale the image to look almost indistinguishable from native resolution.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="links-section">
      <h3>Related Guides</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/gaming-jargon-dictionary">Gaming Jargon Dictionary</a></li>
        <li><a href="/fps-terms-glossary">Fps Terms Glossary</a></li>
        <li><a href="/streaming-terms-glossary">Streaming Terms Glossary</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>


  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // Page specific JS
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .card h3 { color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .card p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .links-section { margin-top: 3rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .links-section h3 { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .links-section ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; }
    .links-section li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .links-section a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold; }
    .links-section a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
